The **spread operator (`...`)** in **JavaScript** is used to **expand** values (arrays, objects, strings, etc.) into individual elements.

It *looks the same* as the rest operator, but its **purpose is opposite**.

***

## ✅ What does the spread operator do?

👉 It **spreads (unpacks)** elements from a collection.

***

## 1️⃣ Spread with **arrays**

Used to copy or merge arrays.

### Example: Copy an array

```js
const arr1 = [1, 2, 3];
const arr2 = [...arr1];

console.log(arr2); // [1, 2, 3]
```

### Merge arrays

```js
const a = [1, 2];
const b = [3, 4];

const merged = [...a, ...b];
console.log(merged); // [1, 2, 3, 4]
```

✅ Creates a **new array**

***

## 2️⃣ Spread with **objects**

Used to clone or merge objects.

### Example: Copy an object

```js
const user = { name: "Raju", age: 25 };
const copy = { ...user };

console.log(copy); // { name: "Raju", age: 25 }
```

### Merge objects

```js
const address = { city: "Hyderabad" };

const fullUser = {
  ...user,
  ...address
};

console.log(fullUser);
// { name: "Raju", age: 25, city: "Hyderabad" }
```

✅ If keys are same, **last one wins**

***

## 3️⃣ Spread with **function calls**

Pass array values as individual arguments.

```js
function add(a, b, c) {
  return a + b + c;
}

const nums = [1, 2, 3];
add(...nums); // 6
```

***

## 4️⃣ Spread with **strings**

Strings can also be spread.

```js
const name = "Raj";
const letters = [...name];

console.log(letters); // ["R", "a", "j"]
```
